title: For Sale:  Ak 47 Yugo M70B1 great rifle with extras!
postcontent:
This is an early import M70B1 Yugo AK. These are getting harder to come by. Not nearly as common as your civillian marketed zastava n-paps or o-pap underfolders.

This one has the original wood, as well as the reputable US made D.C. Industries thick 1.5mm rpk style receiver with bulged trunnions particular to the B1 and B2 O-PAP. Also the high quality american made 4140 steel green mountain barrel. Built like a tank. Runs like a top. I have put about 500 rounds through it and the original owner didnt shoot it much at all. 

Very accurate. High quality AK. Definitely a big step up from your standard WASR, and if you do the research you will find these earlier Century imports have a great reputation for being solid and accurate. SN# is in the high 4000s.

I kept it pretty basic but have added a couple nice upgrades. You get a tapco slotted muzzle brake, as well Hogue grips/yugo specific handguards(about a month old) so your rifle is ready for a foregrip/whatever else. of course you get the original wood handgaurds as well.  Also have 3 nice steel mags with it. That's about $100 in accessories if you assume most AK's come with 1 mag. Also the wood is left untreated can easily be cleaned up/refinished without having to strip it. 

I travel between Cleveland - Akron - Youngstown for work. Price is pretty firm, no lowballers please, but I will consider all reasonable offers. i'm not pressed to sell it at all. Hate to see it go. Just want to put some money towards my AR or an SVD.

Thanks for looking!

title: For Trade:  Read Entire:  Taurus Millennium G2 .40 S&W
postcontent:
Ok so I took my wife shooting.  She had a blast, literally and figuratively.  I had borrowed a Sig 239 from a buddy and she shot it well.  She wanted her own gun.  I couldn't afford a $700+ Sig.  I bought her this Taurus.  I shoot a .40 so I thought the two of us having one common ammunition would be economical.  I've taken her to shoot it twice, about 100 rds each time.  She hates the recoil.  After the first time I thought I could talk her out of the recoil fear but she's still pushing shits down and says she wants something with less "kick."  

I admit I wasn't very thoughtful in my buying decision.  It's a great little gun.  It shoots well.  It's well made, nice looking and has had no failures.  It has 2- 10rd mags. I'm looking to trade it for something softer shooting.  I'm thinking 9mm but I'm open to here what sorts of trades anyone is interested in.  For the right trade I'll be willing to add cash.  I have about $350 in the gun so please don't try and trade a raven or high point or any other junk guns.

title: For Trade:  !911 Experts and Enthusiasts
postcontent:
I have recently acquired a Series '80 Colt MK IV GCNM in 45ACP.  It took me 30 years to find one that was not union made, but I finally got mine.  I am not necessarily new to the 1911 as I used one often while on active duty, however, I am not as knowledgeable as others on this model.  It seems there is much discussion on the Series '70 versus Series '80, plastic in the 1911 models, collet bushing versus solid, and so on.  I also own two Ruger SR1911 CMD pistols (to which I can attest are ALL METAL except for the grips.)  The "oddest" thing I noticed about my Gold Cup is the guide rod.  It is a spring loaded two piece (metal) unit that is 2 1/8 inches long and depresses to just under 2 inches.  It also has a plastic MSH which surprised me.

I have fired about 100 rounds through the GCNM, 230GR FMJ Ball and JHP.  All fed, fired, and cycled flawlessly.  Some may say "If it ain't broke don't fix it" but here are my questions anyway:

1.  What is the intended purpose of this style guide rod and is it factory stock?
2.  Would I be better served installing a regular GI style guide rod?
3.  Would I be better served installing a solid bushing?  
(I know the intended purpose of the colleted bushing and supposedly they are prone to breakage.)

The only thing I have done to date is remove the idiot scratch and other nicks, install custom grips, and install a new recoil spring (which I do to all used guns upon acquisition and annually thereafter.)  This is my first project gun and although I do not want to "trick it out" or make it a pimp gun by adding curb feelers, I do want to make it as sweet a shooter as possible.  Presently it just does not feel as good as my Ruger models when I squeeze off rounds (and it's more than just the three quarter inch difference in length.)

Thanks from an old Crusty Retired Navy Chief.
